@Database CFG_FCheck

@Index HBBS:Docs/Misc/Index.guide/MAIN

@Node Main "HBBS:System/FCheck - Config File"

  Description
  ===========

  The "HBBS:System/FCheck" file defines the options and commands that
  are used to check uploaded files for corruption.

  If a corrupt file is found, the file is moved to the BADFiles directory
  for the current conference, as specified by the @{"ConfConfig/BadFiles_XX" link HBBS:Docs/Configuration/ConfConfig.Guide/BadFiles_XX} option
  in the conferences "ConfConfig" file.

  Messages will also be loggedin the callers log and the main error log file.

  Options
  =======

  All options must be specified for each type of file.

  Where <ext> is the extension of a file, e.g. for "test.lha" it would be "LHA"

    FileTypeDesc_<ext>=<String>    @{" More... " link FileTypeDesc}
    CheckerCMD_<ext>=<String>      @{" More... " link CheckerCMD}
    CheckerParams_<ext>=<String>   @{" More... " link CheckerParams}
    Error_<ext>=<String>           @{" More... " link Error}

  Example
  =======

  FileTypeDesc_LHA=LHA Archive
  CheckerCMD_LHA=LHA
  CheckerParams_LHA=t -Qa -M -N @F@
  Error_LHA_1=Error on file
  Error_LHA_2=WARNING:
  Error_LHA_3=skipping corrupt
  Error_LHA_4=Operation not entirely successful

  Say you were on node 3 an uploaded TEST.LHA using the above settings, the
  actual command that would be executed would be:

  LHA t -Qa -M -N TEST.LHA

@EndNode

@Node FileTypeDesc "FileTypeDesc"

  FileTypeDesc_<ext>=<String>

    E.G.

    FileTypeDesc_LHA=LHA Archive

    No Default, Must Be Set!

    This is a string that is displayed to the users, telling them what
    kind of file is being checked.

@EndNode

@Node CheckerCMD "CheckerCMD"

  CheckerCMD_<ext>=<String>

    E.G.

    CheckerCMD_LHA=LHA

    No Default, Must Be Set!

    This option specifies the actuall amigados program to run.

    The current directory is set to the node's playpen directory before the
    command is run.

    The command must be in the path, otherwise you must specify a full path
    and file name, e.g. CheckerCMD_LHA=SYS:Utilities/Archivers/LHA

    The command you use must be able to have all of it's output re-directed
    to a file using standard redirection.  e.g. For LHA you might try
    "LHA >ram:test t my_file.lha" to see if it works.

@EndNode

@Node CheckerParams "CheckerParams"

  CheckerParams_<ext>=<String>

    E.G.

    CheckerParams_LHA=t -Qa -M -N @F@

    No Default, Must Be Set!

    This option specifies the paramaters to be passed to the checker.
    It should include things like the filename and any switches to put the
    program into TEST mode.

    If the checker has switches to make the output as small as possible
    then use them.  Also, if the checker has options to use simple IO
    and/or no ANSI then use those options too.

    The checker command string is checked for @ codes, the following
    are recognised:

    @F@ is replaced with the filename of the uploaded file
    @N@ is replaced with just the filename of the uploaded file
    @E@ is replaced with the filename's extension
    @P@ is replaced with the path of the filename (but not including the name itself)

    So, say you were on node 3 and uploaded TEST.LHA the following @ codes
    above would give you the following results (without the quotes)

    @F@ "TEST.LHA"
    @N@ "TEST"
    @E@ "LHA"
    @P@ "HBBS:Nodes/Node3/Playpen/"

@EndNode

@Node Error "Error"

  Error_<ext>_XX=<String>

    E.G.

    Error_LHA_1=Error on file
    Error_LHA_2=Operation not entirely sucessful

    No Default, Must Be Set!

    This option tells the checker door what to look for in the output
    from the checker command.  If it finds one of the strings you
    specify the file will be marked as corrupt.

    If possible, use the correct output order of messages, e.g. for
    LHA the message "Error on file" will always appear before
    "Operation not entirely sucessful", so they should be specified in
    that order to speed up detection of corrupt files.

    To find out what error messages your test program will display
    you have two options:

    1) open the executable of the checker and search it for legible
       error messages (be aware of programs that use catalogs!)

    2) create a file and randomly change and remove bytes from the
       file in several locations (front, middle and end) and run
       the checker program on it a few times to see what comes up.

@EndNode

